Working with Structural Data
\layout Section

Structural Data
\layout Standard

Data produced in structural biology is as diverse as the field itself.
 
\layout Standard

In DINO, the structural data is divided into four different types:
\layout Description

structure A collection of atoms forming a macromolecular structure, organized
 into chains and residues.
 Multiple versions of the same structure can be present, either different
 models or several timeframes from a trajectory.
 See 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \vref{struct_ds}

\end_inset 

.
\layout Description

scalar\SpecialChar ~
field A 3 dimensional grid with a scalar value at each grid position.
 Typically an electron density or an electrostatic potential.
 See 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \vref{scal_ds}

\end_inset 

.
\layout Description

surface A macromolecular surface approximated by triangles.
 See 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \vref{surf_ds}

\end_inset 

.
\layout Description

topograph A 2 dimensional grid with a height value at each position, usually
 obtained from AFM imaging.
 See 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \vref{topo_ds}

\end_inset 

.
\layout Standard

Upon loading a file, it is stored in a database as a single 
\emph on 
dataset
\emph default 
.
 The number of datasets that DINO can hold in its database is only limited
 by the amount of memory available.
 
\layout Standard

In addition, a fifth dataset, 
\series bold 
geom
\series default 
, is available to store geometric primitives (points, lines, triangles and
 rectangles), see 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \vref{geom_ds}

\end_inset 

.
\layout Section

Loading Datasets
\layout Standard

Datasets are loaded from a file into the database with the following command
\layout Code

load FILENAME [-type T] [-name N] [-swap]
\layout Standard

The only mandatory item is the filename.
 If the type is not explicitely given, it is guessed from the file extension.
 Table 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \vref{dbm_load}

\end_inset 

 lists all supported file formats with their expected extensions and the
 type.
 The dataset can be explicitely named with the 
\family typewriter 
-name
\family default 
 option, otherwise the filename without extension will be used.
 The 
\family typewriter 
-swap
\family default 
 flag only applies to binary files and is necessary when a file is loaded
 which was generated on a architecture with a different byte order
\begin_float footnote 
\layout Standard

For values that require more than a single byte, such as integers and floating
 point values, there are two ways to interpret the sequential bytes: Little
 Endian (storing the LSB, least significant byte, first) or Big Endian (storing
 the MSB, most significant byte, first).
\end_float 
 (see Table 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \vref{byte_order}

\end_inset 

).
