Dataset Transformation
\layout Standard

A dataset, and with it all its objects, can be rotated and translated relative
 to other datasets.
 The transformation depends on a 3x3 rotation matrix (
\begin_inset Formula \( R \)
\end_inset 

), a translation vector (
\begin_inset Formula \( T \)
\end_inset 

) and a center of rotation vector (
\begin_inset Formula \( C \)
\end_inset 

).
 The transformed point 
\begin_inset Formula \( P' \)
\end_inset 

 is obtained from the original point 
\begin_inset Formula \( P \)
\end_inset 

 according to
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \[
P'=[R\cdot (P-C)+T]+C\]

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

Four dataset properties are available to set or retrieve the current transformat
ion:
\layout Description


\family typewriter 
rot
\family default 
 a 3x3 rotation matrix in the form 
\family typewriter 
{{a,b,c},{d,e,f},{g,h,i}}
\layout Description


\family typewriter 
trans
\family default 
 a vector in the form 
\family typewriter 
{x,y,z}
\layout Description


\family typewriter 
center
\family default 
 a vector in the form 
\family typewriter 
{x,y,z}
\layout Description


\family typewriter 
rtc
\family default 
 a 4x4 matrix containing rotation, translation and the center
\layout Standard

Initially, the rotation is the identity matrix, the transformation vector
 is zero, and the center is the geometric center of the dataset.
\layout Standard

The following dataset commands are also part of the dataset transformation:
 
\layout Standard

rotx roty rotz
\layout Standard

transx transy transz
\layout Standard

reset [center]
\layout Standard

fix
\layout Standard

grab INPUTDEVICE
